data.content:
Here's the xUnit equivalent:

**Per-test setup** (`[SetUp]`) → **constructor**
**Per-test teardown** (`[TearDown]`) → **`IDisposable.Dispose`**
**One-time setup/teardown** (`[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`) → **`IClassFixture<T>`** with a shared fixture class

```csharp
// Shared fixture handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // was [OneTimeSetUp]
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // was [OneTimeTearDown]
    }
}

// No [TestFixture] needed — xUnit is convention-based
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]  // was [Test]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` constructor |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | Fixture's `Dispose` |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` | `Assert.NotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.EqualTo(y))` | `Assert.Equal(y, x)` |

xUnit creates a **new class instance per test** (like NUnit), so the constructor/`Dispose` pattern gives you the same per-test isolation. The `DatabaseFixture` instance is shared across all tests in the class and disposed after they all complete.
